result.execSummary:
The defendant Paul A. Folker II was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Intimidate Witness/Person Charged/Felony [Modifiers: Increased Penalty for Elder Person Victim, Repeater], a class G felony, Wisconsin Statutes 940.43(7).
  • Intimidate Witness/Person Charged/Felony [Modifiers: Increased Penalty for Elder Person Victim, Repeater], a class G felony, Wisconsin Statutes 940.43(7).
  • Intimidate Witness/Person Charged/Felony [Modifiers: Increased Penalty for Elder Person Victim, Repeater], a class G felony, Wisconsin Statutes 940.43(7).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

superMiscConds.notes: If probation or extended supervision is revoked or discharged with outstanding financial obligations, a civil judgment shall be entered against the defendant and in favor of restitution victims and governmental entities for the balance due.  Collections may include income assignment.  This applies to all counts and financial obligations.

Obey all of the rules and regulations of supervising probation agent. Pay supervision fees. Do not possess or consume alcoholic beverages and do not have alcoholic beverages within the residence. Do not possess or consume controlled substances, except by prescription. Do not be in taverns or on any premises licensed for the sale of intoxicating beverages, except restaurants or grocery stores. Submit voluntarily to random tests of blood, breath or urine. Participate in counseling deemed appropriate by agent. Counseling shall specifically include: Anger management / DV counseling, AODA Assessment and follow through with recommended treatment. Actively search for employment, be employed or attend an educational institution or vocational training program. 
* Pay all court costs including all applicable surcharges. 
* Defendant is ordered to submit to a DNA sample & pay the surcharge, notice given to def. in court. 
May not have contact with Paul Folker, unless otherwise permitted by the court/agent.  May not possess any weapons, including firearms.

3:20 PM Prosecuting attorney Alexander Huber in court for the State of Wisconsin. Defendant Paul A. Folker II in court, in custody.  Attorney Gregory Bates in court for Paul A. Folker II. Clerk N. Nobile.
MINUTES: 22CF663/22CF912. Victim rights compliance. Sentencing arguments heard. 

22CF663: 
Count 1: Defendant is sentenced to years in the 7 WSP; 3 years Initial Confinement followed by 4 years of Extended Supervision.  DE is not eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program or the Substance Abuse Program.  

Count 3 & 4: Defendant is sentenced to 1 year in the Kenosha County Jail concurrent to each other and concurrent to count 1. . 

22CF912: 
Counts 1, 3 & 4: Defendant is sentenced to years in the 6 WSP; 2 years Initial Confinement followed by 4 years of Extended Supervision - consecutive to Case 22CF663.  DE is not eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program or the Substance Abuse Program.  

Court costs and DNA surcharges ordered. Defendant is ordered to submit to a DNA sample, notice given to def. in court. Appeal Rights, Firearm Warning & Voting Acknowledgement given.

22CF912:  Defendant entered a plea of guilty to counts 1, 3 and 4; found guilty by the court. On State's motion, counts 2, 5 and 6 are dismissed and read in.

Presentence Investigation ordered.  Sentencing hearing scheduled for October 5, 2022 at 02:30 pm.
